		<h1>What I do</h1>
		<p>
			I'm an interaction designer. That means I design interactions between products and their users. I try to get to know everything I can about the people I design for. Researching their experiences, thoughts, problems and surroundings gives me the ability to not just create a product that <em>works</em>, but to shape a fitting interaction between a product and a person.
		</p>
		<p>
			I'm currently working on an awesome web app, <strong>Mapiq</strong>. My work ranges from determining the product's functionalities to front-end Javascript coding.
		</p>
		<h1>What I've been up to</h1>
		<h2>Industrial Design Engineering</h2>
		<p>
			I spent three years studying Industrial Design Engineering in which I hold a Bachelor of Science degree. Those three years thought me a lot about solving problems in structured design processes. But more importantly, they awoke a burning interest in the ways products influence people's lives.
		</p>
		<h2>Design for Interaction</h2>
		<p>
			This interest led me to my second study choice: in 2013 I obtained an engineering degree in Design for Interaction. I learnt there's more to product design than coming up with the most efficient and cost-effective solution to a problem.
		</p>
		<blockquote>
